export declare const FST_KNOWLEDGE_FULL = "# **FILM SHOT & TECHNIQUE CHEAT SHEET**\n\n---\n\n## **1. SHOT SIZES (FRAMING)**\n\n### **Extreme Wide Shot (Establishing)**\n\n* **What:** Subject is very small or absent; environment dominates.\n* **Use:** Open scenes, define location, show scale.\n* **Evokes:** Isolation, grandeur, insignificance, context awareness.\n\n---\n\n### **Wide Shot (Long Shot)**\n\n* **What:** Full body visible within environment.\n* **Use:** Introduce characters in space; show movement.\n* **Evokes:** Physical presence, spatial grounding, realism.\n\n---\n\n### **Medium Wide (Cowboy Shot)**\n\n* **What:** Frame from mid-thigh up.\n* **Use:** Dialogue with body language; action readiness.\n* **Evokes:** Balance between character and environment; tension readiness.\n\n---\n\n### **Medium Shot**\n\n* **What:** Waist-up framing.\n* **Use:** Standard dialogue coverage.\n* **Evokes:** Natural engagement; conversational neutrality.\n\n---\n\n### **Medium Close-Up**\n\n* **What:** Chest/shoulders up.\n* **Use:** Emotional dialogue moments.\n* **Evokes:** Connection, attention to subtle expression.\n\n---\n\n### **Close-Up**\n\n* **What:** Face fills frame.\n* **Use:** Key emotional beats or realization moments.\n* **Evokes:** Intimacy, intensity, psychological focus.\n\n---\n\n### **Extreme Close-Up**\n\n* **What:** Isolated detail (eyes, hands, object).\n* **Use:** Symbolic emphasis or tension.\n* **Evokes:** Obsession, precision, discomfort, heightened awareness.\n\n---\n\n## **2. CAMERA ANGLES**\n\n### **Eye-Level**\n\n* **What:** Camera aligned with subject\u2019s eyes.\n* **Use:** Neutral storytelling.\n* **Evokes:** Equality, realism, objectivity.\n\n---\n\n### **Low Angle**\n\n* **What:** Camera below subject looking up.\n* **Use:** Power dynamics, dominance.\n* **Evokes:** Authority, intimidation, awe.\n\n---\n\n### **High Angle**\n\n* **What:** Camera above looking down.\n* **Use:** Vulnerability, exposure.\n* **Evokes:** Weakness, surveillance, loss of control.\n\n---\n\n### **Bird\u2019s-Eye (Top-Down)**\n\n* **What:** Direct overhead.\n* **Use:** Spatial clarity, abstraction.\n* **Evokes:** Detachment, fate, system-level perspective.\n\n---\n\n### **Dutch Angle (Tilted Frame)**\n\n* **What:** Frame is slanted.\n* **Use:** Instability, disorientation.\n* **Evokes:** Psychological tension, unease, imbalance.\n\n---\n\n## **3. CAMERA MOVEMENT**\n\n### **Static Shot**\n\n* **What:** No camera movement.\n* **Use:** Let action or dialogue carry scene.\n* **Evokes:** Stability, observation, restraint.\n\n---\n\n### **Pan (Horizontal Rotation)**\n\n* **What:** Camera rotates left/right.\n* **Use:** Reveal information, follow motion.\n* **Evokes:** Discovery, continuity.\n\n---\n\n### **Tilt (Vertical Rotation)**\n\n* **What:** Camera rotates up/down.\n* **Use:** Reveal scale or hierarchy.\n* **Evokes:** Awe (tilt up), inspection (tilt down).\n\n---\n\n### **Dolly In (Push-In)**\n\n* **What:** Camera moves toward subject.\n* **Use:** Emotional emphasis, realization.\n* **Evokes:** Intensity, focus, inevitability.\n\n---\n\n### **Dolly Out (Pull-Back)**\n\n* **What:** Camera moves away.\n* **Use:** Reveal context or isolation.\n* **Evokes:** Separation, loss, detachment.\n\n---\n\n### **Truck (Side Movement)**\n\n* **What:** Camera moves laterally.\n* **Use:** Track subjects in motion.\n* **Evokes:** Fluidity, continuity.\n\n---\n\n### **Crane / Jib**\n\n* **What:** Vertical sweeping motion.\n* **Use:** Large-scale reveals, transitions.\n* **Evokes:** Freedom, transcendence, cinematic scope.\n\n---\n\n### **Handheld**\n\n* **What:** Unstabilized camera.\n* **Use:** Chaos, realism, urgency.\n* **Evokes:** Anxiety, immersion, instability.\n\n---\n\n### **Steadicam**\n\n* **What:** Smooth moving handheld system.\n* **Use:** Follow characters fluidly.\n* **Evokes:** Immersion, presence, dreamlike flow.\n\n---\n\n### **Zoom (Lens Change)**\n\n* **What:** Adjust focal length without moving camera.\n* **Use:** Stylized emphasis.\n* **Evokes:** Artificiality, surveillance, sudden focus shift.\n\n---\n\n## **4. LENS & FOCUS**\n\n### **Wide-Angle Lens**\n\n* **What:** Expands field of view; exaggerates depth.\n* **Use:** Tight spaces, dynamic motion.\n* **Evokes:** Distortion, energy, immersion.\n\n---\n\n### **Telephoto Lens**\n\n* **What:** Compresses distance.\n* **Use:** Isolate subjects; flatten space.\n* **Evokes:** Intimacy at distance, voyeurism.\n\n---\n\n### **Shallow Depth of Field**\n\n* **What:** Only subject in focus.\n* **Use:** Direct attention.\n* **Evokes:** Isolation, subjectivity.\n\n---\n\n### **Deep Focus**\n\n* **What:** Everything in focus.\n* **Use:** Complex staging.\n* **Evokes:** Awareness, realism, layered meaning.\n\n---\n\n### **Rack Focus**\n\n* **What:** Shift focus between planes.\n* **Use:** Reveal importance.\n* **Evokes:** Realization, shifting attention.\n\n---\n\n## **5. EDITING TECHNIQUES**\n\n### **Straight Cut**\n\n* **What:** Immediate transition.\n* **Use:** Standard continuity.\n* **Evokes:** Clarity, efficiency.\n\n---\n\n### **Match Cut**\n\n* **What:** Visual or motion continuity between shots.\n* **Use:** Symbolic or seamless transitions.\n* **Evokes:** Connection, meaning linkage.\n\n---\n\n### **Jump Cut**\n\n* **What:** Time discontinuity within same shot.\n* **Use:** Compress time, create unease.\n* **Evokes:** Fragmentation, urgency.\n\n---\n\n### **Cross-Cutting**\n\n* **What:** Alternating scenes.\n* **Use:** Parallel action.\n* **Evokes:** Tension, convergence.\n\n---\n\n### **Fade In / Out**\n\n* **What:** Gradual appearance/disappearance.\n* **Use:** Scene boundaries.\n* **Evokes:** Passage of time, closure.\n\n---\n\n### **Dissolve**\n\n* **What:** Overlapping transition.\n* **Use:** Passage of time or memory.\n* **Evokes:** Fluidity, continuity, dream state.\n\n---\n\n## **6. SPECIAL SHOTS**\n\n### **Over-the-Shoulder (OTS)**\n\n* **What:** Shot from behind one subject toward another.\n* **Use:** Dialogue scenes.\n* **Evokes:** Perspective alignment, relational context.\n\n---\n\n### **POV Shot**\n\n* **What:** Shows what a character sees.\n* **Use:** Subjective experience.\n* **Evokes:** Identification, immersion.\n\n---\n\n### **Insert Shot**\n\n* **What:** Close-up of object.\n* **Use:** Important detail.\n* **Evokes:** Significance, clue emphasis.\n\n---\n\n### **Cutaway**\n\n* **What:** Brief alternate shot.\n* **Use:** Break continuity or add context.\n* **Evokes:** Expansion of scene awareness.\n\n---\n\n### **Tracking Shot**\n\n* **What:** Continuous follow movement.\n* **Use:** Action or journey.\n* **Evokes:** Momentum, immersion.\n\n---\n\n### **Whip Pan**\n\n* **What:** Fast pan with blur.\n* **Use:** Transition or surprise.\n* **Evokes:** Energy, disorientation.\n\n---\n\n## **7. LIGHTING**\n\n### **High-Key**\n\n* **What:** Bright, low contrast.\n* **Use:** Comedy, commercial, clean visuals.\n* **Evokes:** Safety, clarity, optimism.\n\n---\n\n### **Low-Key**\n\n* **What:** Strong shadows, contrast.\n* **Use:** Drama, noir.\n* **Evokes:** Mystery, tension, depth.\n\n---\n\n### **Backlighting**\n\n* **What:** Light behind subject.\n* **Use:** Silhouettes, separation.\n* **Evokes:** Mystery, transcendence.\n\n---\n\n### **Practical Lighting**\n\n* **What:** Visible light sources in frame.\n* **Use:** Realism.\n* **Evokes:** Authenticity, groundedness.\n\n---\n\n## **8. TIME & MOTION MANIPULATION**\n\n### **Slow Motion**\n\n* **Use:** Highlight moment.\n* **Evokes:** Gravity, emotional weight.\n\n---\n\n### **Time-Lapse**\n\n* **Use:** Compress long durations.\n* **Evokes:** Passage of time, inevitability.\n\n---\n\n### **Long Take**\n\n* **Use:** Continuous action.\n* **Evokes:** Immersion, realism, tension.\n\n---\n\n### **Freeze Frame**\n\n* **Use:** Stop motion.\n* **Evokes:** Reflection, emphasis.\n\n---\n\n## **HOW TO USE THIS IN PRACTICE**\n\n* **Emotional escalation:** Wide \u2192 Medium \u2192 Close-Up \u2192 Extreme Close-Up\n* **Power shift:** Eye-level \u2192 Low angle (dominance) or High angle (submission)\n* **Tension building:** Static \u2192 Slow push-in \u2192 Close-Up\n* **Disorientation:** Dutch angle + handheld + jump cuts\n";
export declare const FST_KNOWLEDGE_COMPACT = "# **FILM SHOT & TECHNIQUE CHEAT SHEET**\n## **1. SHOT SIZES (FRAMING)**\n### **Extreme Wide Shot (Establishing)**\n### **Wide Shot (Long Shot)**\n### **Medium Wide (Cowboy Shot)**\n### **Medium Shot**\n### **Medium Close-Up**\n### **Close-Up**\n### **Extreme Close-Up**\n## **2. CAMERA ANGLES**\n### **Eye-Level**\n### **Low Angle**\n### **High Angle**\n### **Bird\u2019s-Eye (Top-Down)**\n### **Dutch Angle (Tilted Frame)**\n## **3. CAMERA MOVEMENT**\n### **Static Shot**\n### **Pan (Horizontal Rotation)**\n### **Tilt (Vertical Rotation)**\n### **Dolly In (Push-In)**\n### **Dolly Out (Pull-Back)**\n### **Truck (Side Movement)**\n### **Crane / Jib**\n### **Handheld**\n### **Steadicam**\n### **Zoom (Lens Change)**\n## **4. LENS & FOCUS**\n### **Wide-Angle Lens**\n### **Telephoto Lens**\n### **Shallow Depth of Field**\n### **Deep Focus**\n### **Rack Focus**\n## **5. EDITING TECHNIQUES**\n### **Straight Cut**\n### **Match Cut**\n### **Jump Cut**\n### **Cross-Cutting**\n### **Fade In / Out**\n### **Dissolve**\n## **6. SPECIAL SHOTS**\n### **Over-the-Shoulder (OTS)**\n### **POV Shot**\n### **Insert Shot**\n### **Cutaway**\n### **Tracking Shot**\n### **Whip Pan**\n## **7. LIGHTING**\n### **High-Key**\n### **Low-Key**\n### **Backlighting**\n### **Practical Lighting**\n## **8. TIME & MOTION MANIPULATION**\n### **Slow Motion**\n### **Time-Lapse**\n### **Long Take**\n### **Freeze Frame**\n## **HOW TO USE THIS IN PRACTICE**";
export declare const SDS_KNOWLEDGE_FULL = "# Scene Design System\n\n## 1. Start with the dramatic function\n\nBefore choosing shots, define what the scene is doing.\n\nAsk:\n\n* Who has power at the start?\n* Who has power at the end?\n* Is the scene about revelation, tension, intimacy, confusion, wonder, distance, or momentum?\n* Should the viewer feel stable, trapped, invited, overwhelmed, or uncertain?\n* Is the scene externally active or internally active?\n\nThat gives you the visual logic.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core mapping: intention to shot language\n\n## A. To build tension\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Begin wider and more stable\n* Gradually reduce frame size\n* Add selective movement toward subject\n* Increase cutting frequency only if needed\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Medium shots to establish interaction\n* Medium close-ups as stakes sharpen\n* Close-ups when emotional compression begins\n* Slow dolly-in or subtle push-in\n* Shallow depth of field\n* Low-key lighting\n* Occasional insert shots on hands, objects, eyes\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Compression\n* Escalation\n* Psychological narrowing\n* Imminence\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Wide or medium wide to establish spatial relation\n2. Medium two-shot for interaction\n3. OTS coverage\n4. Medium close-up on reaction\n5. Push-in close-up at critical line\n6. Insert on decisive detail\n\n---\n\n## B. To create intimacy\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Favor proximity over spectacle\n* Keep movement restrained and gentle\n* Let faces hold the frame longer\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Medium close-up\n* Close-up\n* Eye-level angle\n* Soft, steady camera\n* Shallow depth of field\n* Longer takes\n* Naturalistic or practical lighting\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Vulnerability\n* Emotional access\n* Trust\n* Human presence\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Medium shot to orient\n2. Medium close-up for mutual attention\n3. Close-up for emotional disclosure\n4. Hold on reaction instead of cutting away\n\n---\n\n## C. To show dominance or threat\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Use angle, framing, and spatial control\n* Make the subject feel structurally larger or more stable than others\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Low angle on dominant character\n* Wider lens close to subject for imposing presence\n* Static or slow deliberate movement\n* Centered composition\n* Backlighting or strong contrast\n* Wider frames showing others arranged around them\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Authority\n* Fear\n* Weight\n* Pressure\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Eye-level group setup\n2. Low-angle medium shot on dominant figure\n3. High-angle reaction on weaker figure\n4. Slow push-in as control tightens\n\n---\n\n## D. To show vulnerability or defeat\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Reduce subject\u2019s visual control\n* Open more empty space around them or look down on them\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* High angle\n* Wide shot with isolation\n* Negative space\n* Pull-back movement\n* Longer lens for emotional flattening\n* Dim or directional light\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Exposure\n* Helplessness\n* Loneliness\n* Emotional diminishment\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Medium shot during active exchange\n2. High-angle medium close-up after loss\n3. Wide pull-back to show isolation\n\n---\n\n## E. To create unease or disorientation\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Break visual stability\n* Disturb horizon, rhythm, or continuity\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Dutch angle\n* Handheld\n* Whip pans\n* Jump cuts\n* Extreme close-ups\n* Wide-angle distortion\n* Fragmented inserts\n* Uneven or flickering light\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Instability\n* Anxiety\n* Mental fracture\n* Loss of orientation\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Start relatively normal\n2. Introduce slight instability in framing\n3. Move to tighter distorted coverage\n4. Add abrupt edits or erratic movement\n\n---\n\n## F. To evoke wonder, awe, or transcendence\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Expand scale\n* Reveal space gradually or majestically\n* Use motion that feels lifted or fluid\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Extreme wide shot\n* Crane or jib\n* Slow tilt up\n* Deep focus\n* Backlight, atmosphere, silhouette\n* Long take\n* Symmetrical or expansive composition\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Vastness\n* Reverence\n* Discovery\n* Enlargement of perspective\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Restrained close framing\n2. Reveal through tilt, dolly, or crane\n3. Full environmental shot\n4. Hold to let scale register\n\n---\n\n## G. To communicate speed, pursuit, or urgency\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Favor directional movement\n* Keep compositions dynamic\n* Maintain clear geography unless chaos is intended\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Tracking shots\n* Handheld or steadicam\n* Trucking movement\n* Wider lenses\n* Shorter shot duration\n* Inserts for critical action beats\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Momentum\n* Pressure\n* Immediate danger\n* Embodied movement\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Wide to define route\n2. Tracking profile or front-facing run\n3. Inserts on feet, door handles, weapon, phone\n4. Cross-cuts if parallel action matters\n\n---\n\n## H. To show revelation or realization\n\n**Visual pattern**\n\n* Shift from external observation to internal recognition\n* Let attention narrow at the moment of discovery\n\n**Useful choices**\n\n* Rack focus\n* Slow push-in\n* Insert shot\n* Close-up reaction\n* Sudden stillness after motion\n* Slight sound or visual simplification\n\n**What it evokes**\n\n* Recognition\n* Cognitive shift\n* Meaning landing\n* Sudden coherence\n\n**Typical sequence**\n\n1. Medium shot with scene activity\n2. Insert or focus shift to key detail\n3. Close-up reaction\n4. Hold for processing\n\n---\n\n## 3. Simple recipe builder\n\nUse this formula:\n\n**Scene intent** + **power structure** + **subjectivity level** + **energy level** = **shot plan**\n\nExample:\n\n**Intent:** tension\n**Power structure:** shifting\n**Subjectivity:** medium-high\n**Energy:** restrained\n**Result:** start with stable medium two-shots, move into tighter OTS coverage, introduce subtle push-ins, end on close-up with shallow depth of field.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Shot progression templates\n\n## Template 1: Dialogue tension escalation\n\nUse when two characters are verbally circling conflict.\n\n1. Wide two-shot\n\n   * Establish relation and distance\n\n2. Medium two-shot\n\n   * Narrow attention to interaction\n\n3. OTS on speaker A\n\n   * Align viewer with one side\n\n4. OTS on speaker B\n\n   * Counterpoint and rhythm\n\n5. Medium close-up on A\n\n   * Stakes sharpen\n\n6. Medium close-up on B\n\n   * Emotional detail becomes visible\n\n7. Close-up on decisive line\n\n   * Compression and impact\n\n8. Reaction close-up\n\n   * Consequence lands\n\n---\n\n## Template 2: Intimate confession\n\n1. Medium shot\n2. Medium close-up\n3. Close-up on confessor\n4. Hold on listener reaction\n5. Return to shared frame only after emotional shift\n\nThis works because intimacy usually strengthens when the frame narrows and cutting slows.\n\n---\n\n## Template 3: Threat entrance\n\n1. Establishing shot of environment\n2. Character notices something off-screen\n3. Slow pan or rack focus reveal\n4. Low-angle medium shot of threatening figure\n5. High-angle or tight reaction on observer\n6. Hold rather than cut rapidly\n\nThis lets threat arrive with shape and weight.\n\n---\n\n## Template 4: Realization beat\n\n1. Medium shot with ongoing action\n2. Insert of clue\n3. Rack focus or push-in\n4. Close-up reaction\n5. Brief pause before next action\n\nThe pause is often what makes the realization feel real.\n\n---\n\n## Template 5: Isolation after loss\n\n1. Close-up during emotional event\n2. Silence or reduced motion\n3. Pull back to medium\n4. Pull back to wide with negative space\n5. Hold\n\nThis turns private pain into spatial fact.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Emotional control through distance\n\nA useful rule:\n\n* **Wide** = relationship to world\n* **Medium** = relationship to others\n* **Close** = relationship to self\n* **Extreme close** = relationship to a single thought, sensation, or symbol\n\nSo when designing a scene, choose whether the viewer should feel the world, the interaction, the person, or the detail.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Emotional control through movement\n\nAnother useful rule:\n\n* **Static** = observation, restraint, certainty\n* **Slow push-in** = attention intensifying\n* **Pull-back** = emotional distancing or contextualization\n* **Lateral tracking** = continuity and movement through process\n* **Handheld** = embodied instability\n* **Crane** = release, scale, elevation\n\n---\n\n## 7. Emotional control through angle\n\n* **Eye level** = equal regard\n* **Low angle** = force, control, stature\n* **High angle** = exposure, reduction\n* **Overhead** = abstraction, destiny, system-view\n* **Dutch angle** = inner or outer imbalance\n\n---\n\n## 8. A fast decision matrix\n\nIf you want the viewer to feel:\n\n**Close to a character**\n\n* medium close-up / close-up\n* eye-level\n* shallow depth of field\n* steady camera\n\n**Unsafe**\n\n* handheld\n* tighter framing\n* low-key light\n* Dutch angle or obstructed composition\n\n**A power imbalance**\n\n* low angle on one subject\n* high angle on the other\n* asymmetrical framing\n* different lensing or distance\n\n**Wonder**\n\n* wide or extreme wide\n* deep focus\n* upward reveal\n* long take\n\n**Mental fragmentation**\n\n* jump cuts\n* extreme close-ups\n* unstable horizon\n* abrupt lens or framing changes\n\n---\n\n## 9. One practical scene generator\n\nYou can use this fill-in structure for any scene:\n\n**Scene goal:**\nWhat changes by the end?\n\n**Primary emotion:**\nTension, grief, intimacy, awe, confusion, dread, triumph\n\n**Power at start:**\nWho controls the scene?\n\n**Power at end:**\nWho controls the scene?\n\n**Viewer alignment:**\nWhose inner state should dominate?\n\n**Visual progression:**\nWide \u2192 Medium \u2192 Close?\nStatic \u2192 Moving?\nLevel \u2192 Tilted?\nShared frame \u2192 Isolated singles?\n\n**Climax shot:**\nWhat is the one shot that carries the scene\u2019s decisive meaning?\n\n---\n\n## 10. Worked examples\n\n## Example: \u201CBuild tension between two characters at a dinner table\u201D\n\n**Goal:** polite conversation becomes threat\n**Primary emotion:** restrained tension\n**Power shift:** balanced to one-sided\n**Viewer alignment:** alternating, then favor the vulnerable one\n\n**Shot sequence**\n\n1. Wide two-shot across table\n2. Medium singles in OTS pattern\n3. Insert of hand tightening on glass\n4. Medium close-up on aggressor, very steady\n5. Medium close-up on vulnerable character, shallower focus\n6. Slow push-in on final accusation\n7. Silent reaction close-up\n8. Wide shot with new emotional distance\n\n**Why it works**\nThe progression reduces social space and increases psychological pressure.\n\n---\n\n## Example: \u201CA character discovers a beautiful hidden valley\u201D\n\n**Goal:** transition from uncertainty to awe\n**Primary emotion:** wonder\n**Power shift:** from human-scale effort to environmental vastness\n**Viewer alignment:** explorer\n\n**Shot sequence**\n\n1. Tight medium following character through brush\n2. Over-the-shoulder partial reveal\n3. Slow step forward with steadicam or dolly\n4. Tilt up or crane reveal into extreme wide\n5. Hold on landscape\n6. Close-up reaction with soft light\n7. Return to wide for scale confirmation\n\n**Why it works**\nYou delay the full reveal so the expansion of the frame becomes the emotional event.\n\n---\n\n## Example: \u201CA person realizes they have been betrayed\u201D\n\n**Goal:** information turns into emotional rupture\n**Primary emotion:** shock into hurt\n**Power shift:** perceived safety to collapse\n**Viewer alignment:** betrayed character\n\n**Shot sequence**\n\n1. Medium conversation shot\n2. Insert on message / object / expression\n3. Rack focus or cut to detail\n4. Close-up on eyes processing\n5. Sound and movement simplify\n6. Slow pull-back as emotional distance opens\n7. Wide isolated frame\n\n**Why it works**\nRevelation lands in a close frame, then expands into emptiness.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Condensed master rule\n\nA scene usually feels strongest when the visual grammar changes with the dramatic state.\n\nIf the scene escalates, the shots should usually compress, intensify, isolate, or destabilize.\n\nIf the scene opens into freedom, truth, awe, or release, the shots should usually widen, lift, steady, or breathe.\n";
export declare const SDS_KNOWLEDGE_COMPACT = "# Scene Design System\n## 1. Start with the dramatic function\n* Who has power at the start?\n* Who has power at the end?\n* Is the scene about revelation, tension, intimacy, confusion, wonder, distance, or momentum?\n* Should the viewer feel stable, trapped, invited, overwhelmed, or uncertain?\n* Is the scene externally active or internally active?\n## 2. Core mapping: intention to shot language\n## A. To build tension\n* Begin wider and more stable\n* Gradually reduce frame size\n* Add selective movement toward subject\n* Increase cutting frequency only if needed\n* Medium shots to establish interaction\n* Medium close-ups as stakes sharpen\n* Close-ups when emotional compression begins\n* Slow dolly-in or subtle push-in\n* Shallow depth of field\n* Low-key lighting\n* Occasional insert shots on hands, objects, eyes\n* Compression\n* Escalation\n* Psychological narrowing\n* Imminence\n## B. To create intimacy\n* Favor proximity over spectacle\n* Keep movement restrained and gentle\n* Let faces hold the frame longer\n* Medium close-up\n* Close-up\n* Eye-level angle\n* Soft, steady camera\n* Shallow depth of field\n* Longer takes\n* Naturalistic or practical lighting\n* Vulnerability\n* Emotional access\n* Trust\n* Human presence\n## C. To show dominance or threat\n* Use angle, framing, and spatial control\n* Make the subject feel structurally larger or more stable than others\n* Low angle on dominant character\n* Wider lens close to subject for imposing presence\n* Static or slow deliberate movement\n* Centered composition\n* Backlighting or strong contrast\n* Wider frames showing others arranged around them\n* Authority\n* Fear\n* Weight\n* Pressure\n## D. To show vulnerability or defeat\n* Reduce subject\u2019s visual control\n* Open more empty space around them or look down on them\n* High angle\n* Wide shot with isolation\n* Negative space\n* Pull-back movement\n* Longer lens for emotional flattening\n* Dim or directional light\n* Exposure\n* Helplessness\n* Loneliness\n* Emotional diminishment\n## E. To create unease or disorientation\n* Break visual stability\n* Disturb horizon, rhythm, or continuity\n* Dutch angle\n* Handheld\n* Whip pans\n* Jump cuts\n* Extreme close-ups\n* Wide-angle distortion\n* Fragmented inserts\n* Uneven or flickering light\n* Instability\n* Anxiety\n* Mental fracture\n* Loss of orientation\n## F. To evoke wonder, awe, or transcendence\n* Expand scale\n* Reveal space gradually or majestically\n* Use motion that feels lifted or fluid\n* Extreme wide shot\n* Crane or jib\n* Slow tilt up\n* Deep focus\n* Backlight, atmosphere, silhouette\n* Long take\n* Symmetrical or expansive composition\n* Vastness\n* Reverence\n* Discovery\n* Enlargement of perspective\n## G. To communicate speed, pursuit, or urgency\n* Favor directional movement\n* Keep compositions dynamic\n* Maintain clear geography unless chaos is intended\n* Tracking shots\n* Handheld or steadicam\n* Trucking movement\n* Wider lenses\n* Shorter shot duration\n* Inserts for critical action beats\n* Momentum\n* Pressure\n* Immediate danger\n* Embodied movement\n## H. To show revelation or realization\n* Shift from external observation to internal recognition\n* Let attention narrow at the moment of discovery\n* Rack focus\n* Slow push-in\n* Insert shot\n* Close-up reaction\n* Sudden stillness after motion\n* Slight sound or visual simplification\n* Recognition\n* Cognitive shift\n* Meaning landing\n* Sudden coherence\n## 3. Simple recipe builder\n## 4. Shot progression templates\n## Template 1: Dialogue tension escalation\n   * Establish relation and distance\n   * Narrow attention to interaction\n   * Align viewer with one side\n   * Counterpoint and rhythm\n   * Stakes sharpen\n   * Emotional detail becomes visible\n   * Compression and impact\n   * Consequence lands\n## Template 2: Intimate confession\n## Template 3: Threat entrance\n## Template 4: Realization beat\n## Template 5: Isolation after loss\n## 5. Emotional control through distance\n* **Wide** = relationship to world\n* **Medium** = relationship to others\n* **Close** = relationship to self\n* **Extreme close** = relationship to a single thought, sensation, or symbol\n## 6. Emotional control through movement\n* **Static** = observation, restraint, certainty\n* **Slow push-in** = attention intensifying\n* **Pull-back** = emotional distancing or contextualization\n* **Lateral tracking** = continuity and movement through process\n* **Handheld** = embodied instability\n* **Crane** = release, scale, elevation\n## 7. Emotional control through angle\n* **Eye level** = equal regard\n* **Low angle** = force, control, stature\n* **High angle** = exposure, reduction\n* **Overhead** = abstraction, destiny, system-view\n* **Dutch angle** = inner or outer imbalance\n## 8. A fast decision matrix\n* medium close-up / close-up\n* eye-level\n* shallow depth of field\n* steady camera\n* handheld\n* tighter framing\n* low-key light\n* Dutch angle or obstructed composition\n* low angle on one subject\n* high angle on the other\n* asymmetrical framing\n* different lensing or distance\n* wide or extreme wide\n* deep focus\n* upward reveal\n* long take\n* jump cuts\n* extreme close-ups\n* unstable horizon\n* abrupt lens or framing changes\n## 9. One practical scene generator\n## 10. Worked examples\n## Example: \u201CBuild tension between two characters at a dinner table\u201D\n## Example: \u201CA character discovers a beautiful hidden valley\u201D\n## Example: \u201CA person realizes they have been betrayed\u201D\n## 11. Condensed master rule";
export declare const SHOTSTACK_KNOWLEDGE_FULL = "# **SHOTSTACK COMPOSITING KNOWLEDGE**\n\n---\n\n## **1. THE TIMELINE**\nShotstack uses a JSON-based timeline to compose videos. The timeline contains an array of `tracks`.\n* **Tracks**: Layers of media. Track 1 is the bottom layer (background), Track 2 is above it, etc. Audio tracks are typically placed on separate tracks from video tracks.\n* **Clips**: Each track contains an array of clips. Clips define the media asset, start time, length, and any effects/transitions.\n\n## **2. ASSETS**\nClips reference assets. Common asset types:\n* **video**: `{ \"type\": \"video\", \"src\": \"url_to_mp4\" }`\n* **audio**: `{ \"type\": \"audio\", \"src\": \"url_to_mp3\" }`\n* **image**: `{ \"type\": \"image\", \"src\": \"url_to_jpg\" }`\n* **title**: `{ \"type\": \"title\", \"text\": \"Hello World\", \"style\": \"minimal\" }`\n\n## **3. EFFECTS**\nEffects add motion to clips. You MUST use one of these exact strings:\n`zoomIn`, `zoomInSlow`, `zoomInFast`, `zoomOut`, `zoomOutSlow`, `zoomOutFast`, `slideLeft`, `slideLeftSlow`, `slideLeftFast`, `slideRight`, `slideRightSlow`, `slideRightFast`, `slideUp`, `slideUpSlow`, `slideUpFast`, `slideDown`, `slideDownSlow`, `slideDownFast`\n\n## **4. TRANSITIONS**\nTransitions blend clips together or fade them in/out. The `transition` object has `in` and `out` keys. You MUST use one of these exact strings:\n`fade`, `fadeSlow`, `fadeFast`, `reveal`, `revealSlow`, `revealFast`, `wipeLeft`, `wipeLeftSlow`, `wipeLeftFast`, `wipeRight`, `wipeRightSlow`, `wipeRightFast`, `slideLeft`, `slideLeftSlow`, `slideLeftFast`, `slideRight`, `slideRightSlow`, `slideRightFast`, `slideUp`, `slideUpSlow`, `slideUpFast`, `slideDown`, `slideDownSlow`, `slideDownFast`, `carouselLeft`, `carouselLeftSlow`, `carouselLeftFast`, `carouselRight`, `carouselRightSlow`, `carouselRightFast`, `carouselUp`, `carouselUpSlow`, `carouselUpFast`, `carouselDown`, `carouselDownSlow`, `carouselDownFast`, `zoom`\n\n## **5. FILTERS**\nFilters adjust the color or style of the clip. You MUST use one of these exact strings:\n`blur`, `boost`, `contrast`, `darken`, `greyscale`, `lighten`, `muted`, `negative`\n\n## **6. OUTPUT RESOLUTION**\nThe `output.resolution` field MUST be one of: `preview`, `mobile`, `sd`, `hd`, `1080`, `4k`\n\n## **EXAMPLE JSON COMPOSITION**\n```json\n{\n  \"timeline\": {\n    \"tracks\": [\n      {\n        \"clips\": [\n          {\n            \"asset\": { \"type\": \"video\", \"src\": \"video1.mp4\" },\n            \"start\": 0,\n            \"length\": 5,\n            \"effect\": \"zoomIn\",\n            \"transition\": { \"in\": \"fade\", \"out\": \"fade\" }\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n    ]\n  },\n  \"output\": {\n    \"format\": \"mp4\",\n    \"resolution\": \"hd\"\n  }\n}\n```";
